d Kingdom","Helicourt, Picardie, France":"Hélicourt, Somme, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Eustace","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Old French form of the Late Greek names <i>Eustakhios</i> and <i>Eustathios</i>. These were evidently of separate origin, the former derived from <i>eu</i> ‘well, good’ + <i>stakhys</i> ‘grapes’, the latter from <i>eu</i> + <i>stēnai</i> ‘to stand’. However, the tradition is very confused. The name was introduced in this form to Britain by the Normans, among whom it was popular as a result of the fame of  St Eustace , a Norman nobleman who was said to have been converted to Christianity by the vision of a crucifix between the antlers of the stag he was hunting."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Eustace de Baliol was born in 1168, in Hélicourt, Somme, Picardie, France, his father, Bernard de Balliol II, was 33 and his mother, Agnes de Picquigney, was 35. He had at least 3 sons with Lady Petronella FitzPiers. He died in 1209, in Barnard Castle, Durham, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1168–1209":"1168–1209","1168–1198":"1168–1198","1191–1229":"1191–1229","1191–1246":"1191–1246","1195–Male":"1195–Surnud","1135–1188":"1135–1188",